# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conservation-reliant-species
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Aerobiologists have traditionally been involved in the measurement and reporting of airborne pollen and fungal spores as a service to those with allergies.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] However, aerobiology is a varied field, relating to environmental science, plant science, meteorology, phenology, and climate change.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The first mention of "aerobiology" was made by Fred Campbell Meier in the 1930s.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The particles, which can be described as Aeroplankton, generally range in size from nanometers to micrometers which makes them challenging to detect.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Aerosolization is the process of a small and light particles becoming suspended in moving air.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Now bioaerosols, these pollen and fungal spores can be transported across an ocean, or even travel around the globe.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Due to the high quantities of microbes and the ease of dispersion, Martinus Beijerinck once said "Everything is everywhere, the environment selects".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] This means that aeroplankton are everywhere and have been everywhere, and it solely depends on environmental factors to determine which remain.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Aeroplankton are found in significant quantities even in the Atmospheric boundary layer (ABL).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The effects on climate and cloud chemistry of these atmospheric populations is still under review.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] NASA and other research agencies are studying how long these bioaerosols can remain afloat and how they can survive in such extreme climates.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The conditions of the upper atmosphere are similar to the climate on Mars' surface, and the microbes found are helping redefine the conditions which can support life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The process of dispersal of aerobiological particles has 3 steps: removal from source, dispersion through air, and deposition to rest.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The particle geometry and environment affect all three phases, however once it is aerosolized, its fate depends on the laws of physics governing the motion of the air.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Pollen and spores can be blown from their surface or shaken loose.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Generally the wind speed required for release is higher than average wind speed.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Some fungi can even be triggered by environmental factors to actively eject spores.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Once released from rest, the aeroplankton is at the mercy of the wind and physics.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The settling speed of spores and pollen vary and is a major factor in dispersion; the longer the particle is floating, the longer it can be caught by a turbulent wind gust.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Wind speed and direction fluctuate with time and height, so the specific path of once neighboring particles can vary significantly.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The concentration of particles in the air decreases with distance from source, and the dispersion distance is most accurately modeled as a power function.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Deposition is a combination of gravity and inertia.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] The fall speed for small particles can be calculated by mass and geometry, but the complex shapes of pollen and spores often fall slower than their estimated speed modeled with simple shapes.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Spores can also be removed from the air from impact; the inertia of the particles will cause them to hit surfaces along their path, instead of flowing around them like air.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] There have been many studies performed to understand real-life dispersal patterns of pollen and spores.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] To collect samples, studies often use a volumetric spore trap such as a Hirst-type sampler.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Particles stick to a sampling strip and then can be inspected under a microscope.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Scientists have to count the particles under magnification, and then analyze sample DNA by Amplicon sequence variant (ASV) or another common method.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] A challenge repeatedly cited in literature is that because of differing testing or analysis methodologies, results are not always comparable across studies.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Therefore, extensive data collection must be performed in each study to get an accurate model.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Unfortunately there is no database of aerobiological particle distribution to compare results to.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Allergic rhinitis is a type of inflammation in the nose that occurs when the immune system overreacts to allergens in the air.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] It is typically triggered in humans by pollen and other bioaerosols.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Between 10% and 30% of people in Western countries are affected.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Symptoms are usually worse during pollination periods, when there is significantly more pollen aerosolized in the air.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] In these peak periods, staying indoors is one way to limit exposure.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] However, studies have shown that there are still significant levels of pollen indoors.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] In the winter, pollen levels indoors actually exceed outdoor levels.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Up to date data on pollen levels is critical for humans that have allergies.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] A current limitation is that many spore traps require scientists to identify and count individual pollen grains under magnification.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] This causes data to be delayed, sometimes by over a week.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] There are currently a number of fully automatic spore traps in development, and once they are fully functional they will improve the lives of people with allergies.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Scientists have predicted that the meteorological results of climate change will weaken pollen and spore dispersal barriers, and lead to less biological uniqueness in different regions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Precipitation increases richness (number of species) of biodiversity in regions because clouds formulate in the upper atmosphere where there is more varied biodiversity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Specifically in the Arctic, climate change has dramatically increased precipitation, and scientists have seen new microbes in the area because of it.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] Rising summer temperatures and CO2 levels have shown to increase total amounts of pollen released by certain trees, as well as delay the start of pollen season.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/aerobiology] However, more studies are needed to see long term effects of climate change.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] This topic of agronomy involves selective breeding of plants to produce the best crops for various conditions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Plant breeding has increased crop yields and has improved the nutritional value of numerous crops, including corn, soybeans, and wheat.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] It has also resulted in the development of new types of plants.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] For example, a hybrid grain named triticale was produced by crossbreeding rye and wheat.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Triticale contains more usable protein than does either rye or wheat.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Agronomy has also been instrumental for fruit and vegetable production research.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Furthermore, the application of plant breeding for turfgrass development has resulted in a reduction in the demand for fertilizer and water inputs (requirements), as well as turf-types with higher disease resistance.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Agronomists use biotechnology to extend and expedite the development of desired characteristics.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Biotechnology is often a laboratory activity requiring field testing of new crop varieties that are developed.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] In addition to increasing crop yields agronomic biotechnology is being applied increasingly for novel uses other than food.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] For example, oilseed is at present used mainly for margarine and other food oils, but it can be modified to produce fatty acids for detergents, substitute fuels and petrochemicals.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Agronomists study sustainable ways to make soils more productive and profitable.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] They classify soils and analyze them to determine whether they contain nutrients vital for plant growth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Common macronutrients analyzed include compounds of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulfur.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Soil is also assessed for several micronutrients, like zinc and boron.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] The percentage of organic matter, soil pH, and nutrient holding capacity (cation exchange capacity) are tested in a regional laboratory.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Agronomists will interpret these laboratory reports and make recommendations to modify soil nutrients for optimal plant growth.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Additionally, agronomists develop methods to preserve soil and decrease the effects of [erosion] by wind and water.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] For example, a technique known as contour plowing may be used to prevent soil erosion and conserve rainfall.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Researchers of agronomy also seek ways to use the soil more effectively for solving other problems.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Such problems include the disposal of human and animal manure, water pollution, and pesticide accumulation in the soil, as well as preserving the soil for future generations such as the burning of paddocks after crop production.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Pasture management techniques include no-till farming, planting of soil-binding grasses along contours on steep slopes, and using contour drains of depths as much as 1 metre.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Agroecology is the management of agricultural systems with an emphasis on ecological and environmental applications.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] This topic is associated closely with work for sustainable agriculture, organic farming, and alternative food systems and the development of alternative cropping systems.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] Theoretical production ecology is the quantitative study of the growth of crops.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] The plant is treated as a kind of biological factory, which processes light, carbon dioxide, water, and nutrients into harvestable products.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/agronomy] The main parameters are temperature, sunlight, standing crop biomass, plant production distribution, and nutrient and water supply.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] The term "conservation-reliant species" grew out of the conservation biology undertaken by *The Endangered Species Act at Thirty Project* (launched 2001) and its popularization by project leader J.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Its first use in a formal publication was in *Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment* in 2005.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Worldwide use of the term has not yet developed and it has not yet appeared in a publication compiled outside North America.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Passages of the 1973 Endangered Species Act (ESA) carried with it the assumption that endangered species would be delisted as their populations recovered.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] It assumed they would then thrive under existing regulations and the protections afforded under the ESA would no longer be needed.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] However, eighty percent of species currently listed under the ESA fail to meet that assumption.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] To survive, they require species-specific conservation interventions (e.g. control of predators, competitors, nest parasites, prescribed burns, altered hydrological processes, etc.) and thus they are conservation-reliant.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] The threats are pervasive and recurrent, for example: nest parasites, non-native predators, human disturbance.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] The threats render the species at risk of extinction, absent ongoing conservation management.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Management actions sufficient to counter threats have been identified and can be implemented, for example: prescribed fires, restrictions on grazing or public access, predator or parasite control.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] National, state or local governments, often in cooperation with private or tribal interests, are capable of carrying out the necessary management actions as long as necessary.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Control of direct human impacts may include control of grazing, human access, on and off-road vehicles, low impact recreation and illegal collecting and poaching.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Pollution control may include control of chemical run-off, siltation, water quality and use of pesticides and herbicides.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Active habitat management may include fire management and control, control of soil erosion and waterbodies, habitat restoration and mechanical vegetation control.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Artificial population recruitment may include captive propagation (forced immigration) or captive breeding.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] A prominent example is in India, where tigers, an apex predator and the national animal, are considered a conservation-reliant species.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] This keystone species can maintain self-sustaining wild populations; however, they require ongoing management actions because threats are pervasive, recurrent and put them at risk of extinction.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] The origin of these threats are rooted in the changing socio-economic, political and spatial organization of society in India.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Tigers have become extinct in some areas because of extrinsic factors such as habitat destruction, poaching, disease, floods, fires and drought, decline of prey species for the same reasons, as well as intrinsic factors such as demographic stochasticity and genetic deterioration.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Recognizing the conservation reliance of tigers, Project Tiger is establishing a national science-based framework for monitoring tiger population trends in order to manage the species more effectively.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] India now has 28 tiger reserves, located in 17 states.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] These reserves cover 37,761 square kilometres (14,580 sq mi) including 1.14% of the total land area of the country.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] These reserves are kept free of biotic disturbances, forestry operations, collection of minor forest products, grazing and human disturbance.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] The populations of tigers in these reserves now constitute some of the most important tiger source populations in the country.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] The magnitude and pace of human impacts on the environment make it unlikely that substantial progress will be made in delisting many species unless the definition of "recovery" includes some form of active management.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Preventing delisted species from again being at risk of extinction may require continuing, species-specific management actions.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] Viewing "recovery" of "conservation-reliant species" as a continuum of phases rather than a simple "recovered/not recovered" status may enhance the ability to manage such species within the framework of the Endangered Species Act.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] With ongoing loss of habitat, disruption of natural cycles, increasing impacts of non-native invasive species, it is probable that the number of conservation-reliant species will increase.
[src:conservation-reliant-species/conservation-reliant-species] It has been proposed that development of "recovery management agreements", with legally and biologically defensible contracts would provide for continuing conservation management following delisting.
